The militarization of domestic life extends beyond immigration. The Trump administration deploys National Guard troops in cities such as Portland, Chicago, and Washington, D.C., without the consent of local leaders, blurring the line between military service and political messaging. At the same time, Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth oversees the firing of several senior officers, including the chair of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, as part of a plan to cut the number of four-star generals and admirals by 20%. A report by six former service secretaries and retired four-star officers warns that these moves, combined with the use of Guard units for immigration enforcement, are politicizing the armed forces. The report calls on Congress to require clear justification and post-action review for domestic deployments and high-level firings. The military thus becomes another arena where loyalty and symbolism threaten to displace professional norms, even as veterans of the system sound the alarm.\
